As the 2023 general elections draw nearer, youths across the country have been warned against unsolicited support to politicians without factoring in their personal and collective interests in the governance of the country. A group, National Youth Inclusive in Governance Association, also berated major political parties for their exorbitant nomination fees, as it was aimed at denying the youths opportunity to participate in the election process to choose or vie for the position of their choice. Convener of the group, Yusuf Sherif Banki, gave the warning at the weekend at the zonal caucus meeting for the North Central zone of the association held in Lokoja, Kogi State capital. Sherif Banki, who noted that the advice became necessary to avoid the pitfalls of the past in which politicians would use and dump the youths immediately the election was won. He averred that from the 2023 election and going forward, his association would only support aspirants and candidates based on written agreement that would benefit the youths in their future relationship in the larger society. He added that his association with membership across the country is open to constructive negotiation with aspirants who would prioritise their welfare during and after the election, before jumping at the carrots. He added that gone were the days when youths would be mobilised by pressing the button of their phones to help them with unwholesome actions, stressing that his group would weigh options before lending their support to aspirants or candidates. He explained that members of the association, mainly from the APC had no anointed aspirants, but were ready to work based on mutually agreed terms at the negotiating table. POLL He urged the youths to close ranks to make sacrifices that would engender good governance in the country in which they would play pivotal roles in the paradigm shift.